Bring a large #saucepan{} of water to the boil with @salt{1/2%tsp} for the pasta.

When boiling, add the @penne pasta{180%g} to the water and bring back to the boil. Cook
until tender, ~{12%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #colander{}.

Pop back into the pan with a drizzle of @oil{} and stir through to stop it sticking
together.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Halve, peel and thinly slice the @echalion shallot{1}.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once the oil is hot, add the @diced chicken breast{260%g} to the pan and season with
@salt{} and @pepper{}. IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw
chicken and its packaging.

Fry until golden brown on the outside, ~{5-6%minutes}.

Add the shallot to the chicken and cook, stirring occasionally, until softened,
~{3-4%minutes}.

Add the garlic and @cajun spice mix{1} (add less if you don't like too much heat) to
the pan. Cook, stirring frequently, for ~{1%minute}.

Add the @water for the sauce{100%ml}, @tomato passata{1} and @chicken stock paste{10}.

Bring to a boil, then turn the heat down to simmer. Cook, stirring occasionally,
until thickened, ~{5-6%minutes}.

Once the sauce has thickened slightly, add the @baby spinach{100%g} a handful at a time
until wilted and piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir through half the @grated hard Italian style cheese{40%g}, followed by the
@creme fraiche{75%g}. Bring to a boil, stirring, then remove from the heat. IMPORTANT:
The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} if needed.

Add the cooked pasta to the creamy sauce and mix well to combine. Reheat until piping
hot if needed.

Share the creamy Cajun chicken pasta between your #bowls{} and sprinkle over the remaining
cheese to finish. Enjoy!

> If you've chosen to get diced chicken breast instead of thigh, cook the recipe in
> the same way.